<br>
It's not what this thread is about so lets leave that argument somewhere else.<br>
<br>
It would be interesting if someone would do some parsings at different strengths and compare their average damage increase to the increase in max damage for the hits that were at max damage.  If the average damage went up in relation to the amount of damage that was increased on the hits that were done for max then we can safely conclude that higher strength simply allows for a higher max damage ceiling.  <br>
<br>
I'm of the opinion that it probably increases all hits rather than just the max damage ones, but the only reason for that opinion is that upping the max damage by 5 points or so is pretty crappy.  (basically I'm just being optimistic, which is probably the wrong stance to take with SoE) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=broddathep>Brodda Thep</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/15/03 11:21 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: not quite the same as atk.</span><hr size=1> THe best known original tests were done on a little lvl 46 warrior gnome in Karnors.  Very few of his hits were for max.  During this time you saw spikes at min hit and at modal hit.  I don't think str would have a very significant affect on the dps of a PC with that distrubution as was shown by his tests.<br>
